# Inventory Management System

![Python](https://img.shields.io/badge/Python-3.11+-blue)
![Version](https://img.shields.io/badge/version-1.0.0-success)
![Tests](https://img.shields.io/badge/tests-214%20passing-brightgreen)
![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-MIT-lightgrey)

A production-oriented **Inventory Management System** built with Python that demonstrates clean software architecture, modular application design, object-oriented programming, automated testing, and business workflow implementation.

The application provides product, customer, inventory, order, invoice, and reporting workflows through a clean, testable command-line interface.

**Version:** 1.0.0  
**Python:** 3.11+  
**Test Status:** All 214 automated tests are passing.

---

## Project Highlights

- Production-oriented Python engineering project
- Clean layered architecture
- Modular service-based design
- Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)
- Automated inventory management
- Automatic invoice generation
- Duplicate invoice prevention
- Comprehensive automated testing
- Well-documented project structure

---

## Project Goals

This project was built to demonstrate production-oriented Python software engineering practices rather than simply implementing CRUD functionality.

The primary goals were to:

- Design a layered architecture
- Separate business logic from presentation
- Build reusable service classes
- Practice Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)
- Implement automated testing
- Create maintainable and extensible code

---

## Features

- Product Management (CRUD)
- Customer Management (CRUD)
- Order Management with multiple order items
- Automatic inventory updates
- Automatic invoice generation
- Manual invoice creation from existing orders
- Duplicate invoice prevention
- Inventory, Sales, Customer, Order, and Invoice reports
- Modular Command-Line Interface (CLI)
- JSON-based data storage
- Comprehensive automated unit tests

---

## Key Engineering Concepts

This project demonstrates:

- Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)
- Clean Architecture
- Separation of Concerns
- Layered Application Design
- Service Layer Pattern
- Modular Application Structure
- JSON Persistence
- Automated Testing with pytest

---

## Architecture

The application follows a layered architecture that separates user interaction, business logic, domain models, and data persistence.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    User --> CLI

    CLI --> ProductMenu[Product Menu]
    CLI --> CustomerMenu[Customer Menu]
    CLI --> OrderMenu[Order Menu]
    CLI --> InvoiceMenu[Invoice Menu]
    CLI --> ReportMenu[Report Menu]

    ProductMenu --> Services
    CustomerMenu --> Services
    OrderMenu --> Services
    InvoiceMenu --> Services
    ReportMenu --> Services

    Services --> Models
    Services --> StorageService[Storage Service]
    StorageService --> Database[storage/database.json]
```

### Layer Responsibilities

#### CLI

- Collects user input
- Displays formatted output
- Coordinates application workflows

#### Services

- Implements business rules
- Coordinates application workflows
- Performs validation
- Manages products, customers, inventory, orders, invoices, and reports

#### Models

- Define validated domain entities
- Represent application data
- Support serialization and deserialization

#### Storage

- Persists application data
- Reads from and writes to the JSON database

---

## Project Structure

```text
inventory_system/
│
├── cli/                 # CLI menus, display helpers, and input handling
├── docs/                # Project documentation
├── models/              # Domain models and enums
├── services/            # Business logic and workflow coordination
├── storage/
│   └── database.json    # JSON database
├── tests/               # Automated unit tests
├── utils/               # Shared utilities and validation
├── config.py            # Application configuration
├── main.py              # Application entry point
├── pyproject.toml       # Project configuration
├── CHANGELOG.md         # Project changelog
├── LICENSE              # MIT License
└── README.md
```

